<div id="main_content">
	<h2>UCFs Honors Service-Learning Program Lauded as 'Leading Example in Nation'</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Zenaida Gonzalez Kotala
		
		<span class="date">Oct. 11, 2006</span></p>
	
	
	
		<div class="article_img" style="width: px;">

			<img alt="Article Main Picture" src="../resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/0/NE843/en_US/backpack_big.jpg" height="" width=""  /> 
			
				<p class="photo_credit">Photo: Jacque Brund</p>
			
			<p>UCF students board buses, which transport them to local elementary schools. There the honor students teach youngsters about social studies and civic responsibility.</p>
			
				<p class="note"><a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=0024004105bd60439010c0c76ce2f00593c">Full Photo</a></p>
			
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
		</div>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:kastro@mail.ucf.edu">Kelly Astro, Burnett Honors College</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-6402 </li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:zkotala@mail.ucf.edu">Zenaida Gonzalez Kotala</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-6120</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.honors.ucf.edu/Default.asp">UCF's Burnett Honors College</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.compact.org/">Campact Compass</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>All Burnett Honors College freshmen at the University of Central Florida teach in some of the most underserved elementary schools in Orlando as part of a course that covers civic responsibility and the history of American community. </p><p /><p>The semester-long Honors Symposium is on the cutting edge of service learning because it integrates substantial field work with the rigor of an academic course, national experts say. The graded course is required of all 480 freshmen during their incoming semester.</p><p /><p /><p>This service-learning course is a partnership between the university, Orange and Seminole County public schools and the nonprofit Junior Achievement of Central Florida. Through Junior Achievement, college students provide a social studies curriculum to more than 9,100 K-5 students in 19 elementary schools. UCF students receive intensive training that covers everything from proper dress and classroom management to professionalism and presentation techniques to ensure that they are fully prepared before they set foot in an elementary school.</p><p /><p /><p>&quot;We want students to be well-rounded,&quot; said Kelly Astro, the director of Research and Civic Engagement for the college. &quot;We want them to be academically successful but also to walk away from their service experience knowing that it is their responsibility to give something back to the greater community and to be engaged, global citizens.&quot;</p><p /><p /><p>UCF students are visiting their schools six times during the six weeks beginning Sept. 18 on buses provided by American Coach Lines. For the rest of the semester, they complete required readings such as Alexis de Tocqueville's &quot;Democracy in America&quot; and passages from Jonathan Kozol's The Shame of a Nation. They also attend a weekly seminar to hear UCF faculty speak on civic responsibility and the evolution of community. </p><p /><p>Each student is mentored by a team leader  an upperclassman who has already taken the symposium  who leads discussion sessions that help students relate their reading assignments, service experiences and fields of study to their daily lives.</p><p /><p /><p>The course grade is based on students' journals, a paper that relates their service experiences to in-class learning, active participation and an evaluation by the classroom teacher at the elementary school.</p><p /><p /><p>The Burnett Honors College program is unique, said Bob Hogner, a consultant for Campus Compact, a national coalition of nearly 1,000 college and university presidents dedicated to promoting community service, civic engagement and service learning in higher education. </p><p /><p>&quot;There's academic learning that's going on there and not just community service,&quot; he said. &quot;They're learning things in the classroom that they can take out to their community, and the work they do there helps make those lessons relevant to their real life.&quot;</p><p /><p /><p>According to 2005 statistics from Campus Compact, about 37 percent of universities required a service-learning component for students, but most were offering courses that combine optional and required portions. The honors course at UCF, however, is not optional, and the service-learning requirement forces students to think critically.</p><p /><p /><p>&quot;I'd say it's a leading example in the nation,&quot; Hogner said.</p><p>Hogner said students who are involved in service learning tend to feel more connected to their communities, both on and off campus. In the long run, they also tend to become people of influence who get things done in the corporate and non-corporate worlds.</p><p /><p /><p>The class teaches students to become or hone their skills as active learners, said Gaston Blanchet, who completed the symposium last year and is a team leader this semester. Not only do the students learn through this, but they provide education and resources to the Orlando community.</p><p /><p /><p>Other UCF colleges partner with Junior Achievement as well. More than 300 students each semester in the College of Business Administration teach classes and complete school-based projects like Field Days and Teacher Appreciation Days as part of the required Cornerstone Course. And the College of Education began a JA partnership more than ten years ago. In each of those cases, service learning is part of the final years of study just as students are ready to enter the workforce. </p>
		
	
